[This is an unusual version of a common event, such as the slaughter and butchering of an animal sick with anthrax. Usually it is from a cow, or a sheep or goat. To be frank I don't think I have heard of an equine source before but this is not to say that horses don't get sick from anthrax. It is common enough. And with the preference for eating horse meat in Central Asia it must be seen there now and again.

Although this has yet to be laboratory confirmed as an anthrax outbreak, I think we can assume from the events and symptoms that it is anthrax. In Indonesia the last recorded outbreak of equine anthrax was in 1996 when 31 horses were affected. Anthrax is common in South Sulawesi with bovine outbreaks in 2002, 2005, 2006, 2009, 2010, and 2012. The most recent human cases there were in 2009 with 11 cases and in 2010 when there were 5 cases with 3 deaths.

Characteristically horses get infected via fly bites and suffer a cutaneous form of the disease as a result. If I am correct there will have been some coincident livestock deaths in the village. Our 2012 posting [see archive no. 20120608.1161664] had 100 cattle in 2 Takalar villages so the disease is a serious livestock problem in this regency in South Sulawesi.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Indonesia can be seen at http://healthmap.org/r/77fI.
To find Sulawesi, go to http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/indonesia_adm_2002.jpg.
To find Takalar in South Sulawesi/Sulawesi Selatan, go to http://www.fallingrain.com/world/ID/38/Takalar.html.
- Mod.MHJ]
